<DOC><DOCNO> AP890316-0183 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2138EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-Hostages-Senate     03-16 0145</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostages-Senate,150</SECOND><HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages</HEAD><HEAD>Senate Resolution Marks Fourth Anniversary of Anderson's Capture</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate marked the fourth anniversary of thekidnapping of Terry Anderson in Lebanon by passing a resolution onThursday calling for the release of all hostages.   The Senate, on a voice vote, said it ``condemns all forms ofhostage taking for whatever purposes by individuals, groups orgovernments.''   It called on countries ``to condemn all forms of hostage takingand to work for the release of all hostages.''   Anderson, The Associated Press' Middle East bureau chief, waskidnapped in Beirut on March 16, 1985.   Eight other Americans are missing in Lebanon and believed heldhostage by groups operating there: Thomas Sutherland, Frank Reed,Joseph James Cicippio, Edward Austin Tracy, Jesse Turner, RobertPolhill, Alann Steen, and William Higgins.   The measure was introduced by Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.</TEXT></DOC>